7. Components of an HTTP Request

A request contains several parts.

| Component | Purpose                |
| --------- | ---------------------- |
| URL       | API address            |
| Method    | GET or POST            |
| Headers   | Additional information |
| Body      | Data sent to server    |

Example:

POST /chat

Question:
Recommend pizza.

=====

8. Components of an HTTP Response

The server sends:

| Component   | Purpose              |
| ----------- | -------------------- |
| Status Code | Success or Error     |
| Headers     | Response information |
| Body        | Actual data          |


Example:

Status

200 OK

Body

Chicken Pizza

₹250
9. Request Headers

Headers provide extra information.

Examples:

Content-Type

Authorization

Accept

User-Agent

Our chatbot mainly uses:

Content-Type

application/json

This tells Flask that the data is JSON.

10. Request Body

The Body contains the actual data sent to the server.

Example:

{
   "message":"Recommend a pizza"
}

Flask reads this message and forwards it to Gemini.

11. Response Body

Gemini generates:

{
   "response":"I recommend Veg Pizza."
}

Flask sends this JSON back to the website.

12. JSON Format

JSON stands for

JavaScript Object Notation

It is the most common format for APIs.

Example:

{
   "name":"Sugumar",
   "food":"Chicken Burger",
   "quantity":2
}

JSON is:

Easy to read
Easy to send
Easy for Python and JavaScript to process
13. HTTP Status Codes

Servers return status codes.


| Code | Meaning               |
| ---- | --------------------- |
| 200  | Success               |
| 201  | Created Successfully  |
| 400  | Bad Request           |
| 401  | Unauthorized          |
| 403  | Forbidden             |
| 404  | Page Not Found        |
| 500  | Internal Server Error |


